<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-790-534  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 790 534.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  August 1990 v63 n8 p64(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Choosing to be linked. (industry, government, and the public mustwork together for a networked future) (Eye on the Industry)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Marano, Rocco J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>North American telecommunications are being pushed towardintegration by advances in technology, increasing standardizationand customer demand for better information access.andP;  Technologicalimprovements such as fast digital switches, large-bandwidthfiber-optic cable and intelligent network systems are beginning tobe used across North America, and their capabilities will supportlarge-scale network integration.andP;  Some antitrust laws andattitudes prevent companies from cooperating on technologyexpansion and use, so the government should should encourage suchcooperation by changing the laws.andP;  Industry should continue toaccelerate its standardization effort to help achieve the goal ofa connected continent.andP;  As technology and policy changes makenetwork integration feasible, the consumer need for improvedinformation exchange could be fulfilled.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     NetworksStandardizationOutlookConnectivity.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>